            user: 'zlrObJ++dL34B24/H04caA==',
            reviewDate: 'November 26, 2023',
            semester: 'fall 2023',
            review: 'This course was my first in the program, and it was a great class to get back into school. For reference, my background is in aerospace engineering with a pretty good working knowledge of python and its various packages. I am married and working full time doing CV things (out of school for almost 4 years), but do not have a kid. So I have more free-time compared to a new parent who works full-time, but less\nFor me, I would say I averaged about 8 hours a week (maybe less). I had a couple of week I would do 10-20 hours, but more often I did not touch the course at all. It could also be completely front-loaded with all material being released in the first month-ish, and never touch it again except for the exams.\nI found the projects to be engaging and fairly intuitive. Sometimes the descriptions were poorly worded or sparse in areas that could use more description and wordy in areas that made it more complicated than it needed to me. However, nothing that a bit of debugging the supplied code and doing some planning could resolve though. The projects were also directly correlated (in a simplified version) with concepts that were applicable to my actual work, or things that I was interested in working on which was cool. TAs and students were helpful and there are a lot of office hours and resources for those who are struggling.\nSome gripes I do have though, is the lecture videos are a bit dated (11ish years at the time of me taking the class to be exact). The videos, as well as the projects, are a bit sparse in a way. They never dove as deep as I wish they would. Projects could easily be completed by using the code from the lectures they provided and modifying it in a way that fit a slightly more complex structure. This often got me to around ~95% where tuning some variables would get the extra 5%, but often at the cost of boring hours of changing then testing. To me, that time was not usually worth it unless I had a good idea of what needed to be tuned. I likely could have reduced my average hours by 1 or 2 if I decided not to tune at all and leave my scores in the mid 90s. Lastly, the tests are not difficult, but it did seem up to luck on whether you would have enough time. Additionally, there is no good study materials for the exams. The "study quiz" is filled with pretty rudimentary questions where few calculations are needed (giving a false sense of what might be on the test), but on the test the questions are more difficult requiring more detailed knowledge of the equations and steps used. You are given 2 chances on the tests though, so you have more time to study if you planned accordingly. Additionally, there is extra credit, but the amount of extra credit (2%) seems so low for the level of effort they seemed to require.\nOverall, I found the course interesting. Even though the subjects taught are basic versions of the algorithms used more often in industry it gives you good building blocks. I do wish it was a bit more in-depth touching on derivations and the more advanced versions of concepts learned, but overall I learned a tremendous amount that I have already been able to apply and was not too stressed doing it. I would say if you do not have interest in things like Kalman-Filters or SLAM and their applications then this is a pass.',
