            reviewDate: 'August 12, 2023',
            semester: 'summer 2023',
            review: "Background: MechE major, I had some prior coop experience as a control engineer, but had limited python knowledge. 2nd OMSCS course, paired with incredibly stressful day job where I work on dynamic systems.\nProblem Sets: Trivial, solutions are already provided in lectures. However, useful to do latter problem sets rigorously.\nProjects:\n\nKalman Filter: Excellent. Spent 1 day learning the theory, 1 day implementing.\nParticle Filter: 1.5 days total learning and implementing. Excellent, fairly easy grading.\nPID: Conceptually easy but the difficulty is the twiddle algorithm for tuning. It takes some insight too. Good project. 1 day, gave up on getting full score.\nWarehouse search: Conceptually interesting project (Dynamic Programming, A star). Nice animations. However, there were a ton of weird edge cases in the tests I and many folks didn't complete. Gave up trying to get 100% after 2 days.\nIndiana Drones:  Online SLAM algorithm (introduced in Pset 6 is key). The book-keeping here was a nightmare. Gave up after 3 distracted days with a low 80s score.\n\nMid term: 40 mins, 20 questions. Lectures and Psets were sufficient. 1 day preparation. Nearly perfect on 1st try.\nFinals: 1 hour, 30 questions, comprehensive. 1 day preparation. Approx. 90% on 1st try, was sufficient for solid A overall.\nOverall:\n\nA good overview of many state estimation, control, search algorithms. Nice to know how easy it is to implement these.\nCovers a few good concepts. However, the actually effort of the course can be cut 50% by not having us pour over edge cases. Although this is part of an actual control engineer's job, it feels wasteful to learn in class. On the other hand, these help improve retention of the algorithms.\nGreat exams that test intuition well.\n",
