            user: '6v6NWG6Kl/hPv2eJJuS8gA==',
            reviewDate: 'August 2, 2023',
            semester: 'summer 2023',
            review: "RAIT was a great class with a lot of focused learning and good projects, and it was run in a way that felt fair, straightforward, and without any artificial difficulty. The subject matter is mainly ways of localizing and moving robots in a noisy and uncertain physical environment. Search/planning is also covered.\nThis is my second class at OMS after ML4T, and I thought RAIT was both more challenging, and much less hassle by comparison. I completed some of the RAIT projects in less time than it took to read the assignment specifications in ML4T, and even with the accelerated summer schedule it felt like less of a time commitment.\nRAIT's assignment specs were short and to the point, and I never had a hard time figuring out what to do. There was less tuning of hyperparameters than I expected, though the PID project had a lot of that. I didn't really mind because it's a useful skill for anything related to AI/ML.\nAssignments were graded promptly, I was never left wondering what my grade would be on a project or in the class.\nThough not an ML class, RAIT dives into a lot of probability concepts, and if you have no prior background in probability it might be difficult for you. Some linear algebra was used, but it was pretty lightweight compared to what you have to do in an undergrad level linear algebra class like Georgia Tech's MATH 1554. Calculus is not required, though the concept of the integral and derivative do come up briefly, and it's nice if you understand what those are.\nYou should be comfortable with programming in python, or at least another high level language before taking the class.\nI didn't really have a huge interest in robotics prior to taking RAIT, but it definitely got me wanting to explore the subject more deeply. I didn't have time to do the hardware challenge during the class, but I definitely want to give it a shot in my spare time. Overall great class, and doable over the summer semester.",
