            reviewDate: 'July 31, 2023',
            semester: 'summer 2023',
            review: "I thought this class was a perfect summer class.\nI'll try to add some stuff that is not present in existing course reviews:\n\nPeople say that a lot of time is spent on tuning...I think that is only partially true. If you understand what you are doing, usually the tuning is minimum. There are also some projects (like the particle filter) where I found it next to impossible to pass all of the test cases with a single tuning. However, in cases like this, your test cases are run multiple times to help with some of the randomness and you only have to get like a pass on 15 / 20 to get a perfect score. Tuning was only a little bit, and keep it simple. The projects have great visual debugging, so you can pretty quickly see what is and isn't working.\nFor the summer term, it really helps to plan ahead by looking at the syllabus. Unlike other summer terms, this course does NOT cut out any projects or materials...so expect to sometimes complete multiple lectures in a single week. In one case, we only had 5 days between project due dates. So if you are like me, and plan to take a little summer vacation through the term, it really pays to look work ahead 1 to 2 weeks.\n\nThings that could improve:\nThe professor's lectures and theory is really is really subpar...so temper your expectations. I enjoyed the theory side from RL and the HPC course, but was kind of disappointed when the professor would present classic algorithms like \"magic\" and also refuse to properly identify them (like dijkstra for path finding).\nHowever, I found that the projects made up for this, and the TAs even supplemented a lot of lectures with good tutorial videos in office hours that included more theory and explanation.\nIn all honestly, the TA material was far better than the office hour content.\nAlso, you won't use ML in any sense in this course...so not really a prep course for the actual ML course.\nOverall, I think this is a solid choice for learning about other aspects of AI from a high level (especially robotic control, localization, and path planning). It had just a hint of control systems from electrical engineering and a hints of dynamic programming/policy finding RL to keep me engaged.",
